When debugging data bindings, I often need to set a breakpoint on a particular binding so that I can see if it is firing when I expect and that it is moving the data I expect.

My current coding idiom for doing this is to write binding code like the following and to drop a breakpoint in the indicated location:

      Binding result = ctx.bind(new Property(finalizeTableViewer, 
         ViewersProperties.CONTENT), 
            new TableModelDescription(
               new Property(
                  messagesView.getRoot(), ValidatingView.FIELD_ERROR_MESSAGES, 
                      StatusMessage.class, true), 
               new String[] {
                  "severity", StatusMessage.MESSAGE }), 
               new BindSpec().setModelToTargetConverters(new IConverter[] {
                     new IntToStatusIconViewerLabelConverter(), null }));

      result.addBindingEventListener(new IBindingListener() {
         public ValidationError bindingEvent(BindingEvent e) {
            if (e.type == BindingEvent.EVENT_COPY_TO_TARGET && 
                  e.pipelinePosition == BindingEvent.PIPELINE_AFTER_CHANGE) {
[BREAKPOINT]   return null;
            }
            return null;
         }
      });

When the debugger breaks on the indicated line, then I can inspect the BindingEvent, which contains references to the target and model, so I can then drill down and know if the changes I expected to happen actually happened.

It would be nice if I could instead have debug tooling so that I could drop a data binding breakpoint on the bind() line, with properties of the breakpoint to specify the e.type and e.pipelinePosition on which to break.

Then there could be a separate Eclipse view that would display the current data binding BindingEvent in the same format as the Expressions view, so that I could drill down and view the changes that had occurred.  A "Logical Format" button on the BindingEvent view would be nice too, that would nicely format the current binding event so that novices could understand how data binding is working.

I think the proposal in comment 2 is useful, but I don't understand how it would allow me to break on any arbitrary binding.  I'm also not sure I understand how this differs from the current conditional breakpoints other than having templates for the conditions?

