A simpler, generic way to achieve the same result (until we have tooling) is to add the following to the Binding class:

public class Binding {
   public static class BindingBreakpoint extends Exception {
      public final BindingEvent bindingEvent;
      public BindingBreakpoint(BindingEvent e) { this.bindingEvent = e; }
   }

   public static void breakpoint(Binding binding, 
                                 final int type, final int position) 
   {
      binding.addBindingEventListener(new IBindingListener() {
         public ValidationError bindingEvent(BindingEvent e) {
            if (e.type == type && e.pipelinePosition == position) {
                try {
                   throw new BindingBreakpoint(e);
                } catch (BindingBreakpoint ex) {
                   ex.printStackTrace();  // do something useful here?
                }
            }
            return null;
         }
      });
   }
}

Then the code above could become:

  Binding result = ctx.bind(new Property(finalizeTableViewer, 
     ViewersProperties.CONTENT), 
        new TableModelDescription(
           new Property(
              messagesView.getRoot(), ValidatingView.FIELD_ERROR_MESSAGES, 
                  StatusMessage.class, true), 
           new String[] {
              "severity", StatusMessage.MESSAGE }), 
           new BindSpec().setModelToTargetConverters(new IConverter[] {
                 new IntToStatusIconViewerLabelConverter(), null }));

   Binding.breakpoint(result, BindingEvent.EVENT_COPY_TO_TARGET, 
                      BindingEvent.PIPELINE_AFTER_CHANGE);

Then you could add an Exception breakpoint on BindingBreakpoint in the Eclipse debugger to stop whenever your Binding.breakpoint is triggered.

Similarly, we could have methods for Binding.log(binding, type, position), etc.

